Fiona Apple is gearing up for Saturday&rsquo;s Women&rsquo;s March on Washington with a new song, titled &ldquo;Tiny Hands.&rdquo;
The singer-songwriter teamed up with composer Michael Whalen to create the minute-long track, which Apple recorded on her phone and released Tuesday. The song, which references Donald Trump, is meant to serve as a chant for protesters speaking out against the president-elect, whose inauguration takes place Friday in Washington, D.C.
Sampling Trump&rsquo;s own words from the Access Hollywood tape in which Trump made vulgar comments about women, Apple sings, &ldquo;We don&rsquo;t want your tiny hands, anywhere near our underpants.&rdquo;
Apple previously attacked Trump during the holiday season in a parody of Nat King Cole&rsquo;s &ldquo;The Christmas Song,&rdquo; with the iconic openings lines altered: &ldquo;Trump&rsquo;s nuts roasting on an open fire/as he keeps nipping at his foes/You&rsquo;ll cry creepy uncle/every time he arrives/for he keeps clawing at your clothes.&rdquo;
Trump has denied all accusations of sexual assault and misconduct.
